On the FiveThirtyEight website, there is a clear approval of 42%, as it has only shifted by small decimals for the month of October. In the month of September, there was a constant approval rate that was the same as in October. The most recent shift was in August when his approval rate significantly increased steadily from the prior months. Currently, based on this data, there is a likely chance that by October 31st Biden’s approval rating will stay around 42% or increase. Because 45% is 3% away from 42%, it’s unlikely that his approval rate will increase this much before the end of October.

I almost always get presidential approval wrong, but here goes. As the election is approaching, the White House is doing a better job of managing public opinion than it did a few months ago. The first approval poll post student loan relief showed upward movement in Biden's approval: https://engine-insights.com/blog/public-opinion-polling/ So he stands at 41.9% right now, which is a pretty good cushion. Given that he won 51% of the vote in 2020, these marginal approvals in the 40s are the easiest to win back. Finally, if you go back in time to before mid June, he was always above 40. It shouldn't be too difficult to maintain that, if the White House can just do the bare minimum.

I suspect the current upward momentum won't last, but there's a very real possibility he settles back into his pre-summer band in the low-40s and stays there in the run up to the election. That said, I think he's more likely to drop precipitously than to really gain ground into the upper-40s or to get back to the 50s.

I think Biden has a stronger chance of getting his approval ratings above 40% by Halloween. I think the President will see a bump in the polls as he continues to socialize the wins in IRA. I think the electorate will react well to hearing about reduced drug prices and Medicare being allowed to negotiate drug prices. Health care wins typically help Democrats ( I realize the irons saying this in light of the 2010 midterms).

I'm not super plugged into US domestic politics so I'm making some broad assumptions. Historically, approval ratings under 35% are rare, and haven't really been seen since Bush and the GFC. I wouldn't say we're heading into a GFC level crisis, but recessions are a good determinant of Presidential approval and signs point to a global one on the way. Add on the recent SCOTUS decisions, failure to pass major legislation, and the slow revitalisation of Trumpism in the republican party. I don't see much if any room for his approval to increase. The harder question is timing, and I don't think we'll see it dip below 35 until the mid terms in November.

It's at 38.8 right now, as of July 14. I certainly don't see any major big swings in terms of national mood. I think the President will suffer from a sour national mood. Even if the President were to get a social spending bill across the finish line everyone is going to attack it. Both progressives and republicans will pan it. He wont get a boost from that. Base rates: Presidents rarely get below 35% approval, and when they do it doesn't last long (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/biden-approval-rating/). However, the longest slump was Jimmy Carter between the 2nd and 3rd year of his presidency - during a very high period of inflation (11.3% in 1979 and 13.5% in 1980!) - where he received approval ratings of less than 30%! So there are some parallels to be drawn here with Biden's situation - Americans really do not like high inflation, and they will blame the president when they do.
Guessing based on the economy.
